Pearson correlation coefficient - CORREL(A2:A21, B2:B21)

Population covariance - COVARIANCE.P(A2:A21, B2:B21)
Sample covariance - COVARIANCE.S(A2:A21, B2:B21)


In the bivariate analysis shown in the chart (which plots Hours Spent Studying vs. Exam Score), the values of y and R² are derived from the linear regression trendline equation displayed on the graph.
From the image:
Equation of the trendline (y):
y=5.294x+43.85
This means for every 1 additional hour spent studying, the exam score is predicted to increase by approximately 5.294 points, starting from a base of 43.85.
R² (Coefficient of Determination): R^2 =0.983
This indicates that 98.3% of the variance in exam scores can be explained by the number of hours spent studying — which is extremely strong and suggests a very good linear fit.
These results confirm a strong positive linear relationship between study hours and exam performance.



